Reflection — LSTM-Based LLM Response Evaluation


🔹 What surprised me

One of the most striking insights was how effectively a relatively simple BiLSTM architecture could distinguish between response quality.

The model captured:
Coherence differences
Completeness of explanation
Subtle linguistic quality signals

Despite not using transformers, it achieved:

Test Accuracy: 0.8192
Macro F1: 0.7726

This suggests:

Sequence modeling still retains strong baseline power when combined with good preprocessing and structured input design.

Another key observation:

Including prompt + both responses jointly significantly improved performance
The model learned relative comparison, not just absolute quality




🔹 What failed (and why)
❌ 1. Overfitting after Epoch 3
Training loss kept decreasing
Validation loss increased

Interpretation:

Model began memorizing training patterns
Limited generalization capacity
❌ 2. Limited semantic depth

Compared to transformer models:

Struggled with:
Deep reasoning differences
Nuanced factual correctness
Focused more on surface-level fluency
❌ 3. Vocabulary limitations
Tokenization was simple (split() based)
No handling of:
Synonyms
Contextual meaning
Rare tokens
❌ 4. Class imbalance effects
“Tie” class harder to predict
Model biased toward decisive outcomes
❌ 5. Fixed sequence length constraint
Truncation at max_len=200
Potential loss of important context




🔹 Training Dynamics Insight
Epoch	Key Observation
1–2	Strong learning, stable validation
3	Peak performance (Val Acc: 0.8065)
4–5	Overfitting begins

Best model checkpointing was critical — a strong engineering decision.




🔹 What I would improve with more data
📈 1. Scale dataset (Biggest lever)

More labeled comparisons would:

Improve generalization
Reduce overfitting
Stabilize minority class predictions
🤖 2. Replace LSTM with Transformers

Upgrade to:

BERT / RoBERTa
Cross-encoder architecture

Would:

Capture deep semantic differences
Understand context better
Improve reasoning evaluation
🧠 3. Better tokenization

Replace simple tokenizer with:

Subword tokenization (BPE / WordPiece)

Benefits:

Handles rare words
Improves vocabulary coverage
⚖️ 4. Advanced loss functions
Focal Loss → handle imbalance
Label smoothing → reduce overconfidence
🔗 5. Pairwise ranking formulation

Instead of classification:

Learn A > B ranking score

More aligned with:

Real-world evaluation systems
Reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF)



🔹 Final Takeaway

This project demonstrates that structured sequence modeling can effectively approximate human judgment in response comparison tasks, but scaling to production-grade LLM evaluation requires transformer-based architectures, richer datasets, and ranking-based learning objectives.
